svg:text.svg:tspan: Creating a barrier that keeps oxygen, water or both away from the metal will
prevent corrosion. There are different ways of creating a barrier. For example:
Painting a metal or coating it with a plastic. This is ideal for big and small
structures alike. It has the added advantage that it can be decorative.
uses (p.133) to reduce metal ions onto an
iron electrode. For example, it can be used to coat iron with a layer of a
different metal that won’t be corroded away (see below for more).
Oiling or greasing is used when moving parts are involved. For example,
this is used on bike chains to prevent them from corroding.
You can also prevent rusting using sacricial protection — this involves
placing a more reactive metal with the iron. The water and oxygen react with
this ‘sacricial’ metal instead of the iron in the object you’re protecting.
Galvanising is an example of sacricial protection, where a coat of zinc is
put onto an iron object (such as a bucket) to prevent rusting. The zinc acts
as sacricial protection as it’s more reactive than iron, so it’ll corrode in
preference to iron. The zinc also acts as a barrier.
is a process that uses electrolysis to coat the surface of one
metal with another metal. The cathode is the object that is going to be
electroplated and the anode is a bar of the metal that will end up coating the
surface of the object. The electrolyte is a solution containing the metal ions of
the metal that is being plated on to the object.
Silver can be electroplated onto a brass cup to make it look more attractive.
To do this, you make the brass cup the cathode (to attract the positive silver
ions), and use a bar of pure silver for the anode. Then you dip them both in a
solution of silver ions (for example, silver nitrate). The silver ions in solution
are attracted towards the cathode and silver gets deposited on the cup:
Cathode: Ag + e AgAnode: Ag Ag + e
The anode releases more silver ions into the solution for more electroplating.
